solutions.content:
The main idea is to **use current space instead of creating nodes**. So, we could use ***l1 or l2*** to memorize the results.

1.  If the length of ***l1*** is the same as that of ***l2*** --> nothing special
2.  Else if ***l1*** is shorter than ***l2*** --> we ***'transplant'*** the following ***l2*** to the back of ***l1*** by 
		 `l1->next = l2->next;`
3.  Else if the max size(***l1***,  ***l2***) is still not enough for calculation (for example, ***l1 = 9, l2 = 1***) --> we create a node values 0 and continue the loop.  
		 `l1->next = new ListNode(0);`

```
    ListNode* addTwoNumbers(ListNode* l1, ListNode* l2) {
        int former = 0;
        // assign l1 to head (we'll return head later)
        ListNode* head = l1;
         while(l1) {
             former += (l1 ? l1->val : 0) + (l2 ? l2->val : 0);
             l1->val = former % 10;
             former/=10;
             if(!l1->next && l2 && l2->next) {
                 // if l1 ends but l2 doesn't, we point l1->next to l2->next
                 l1->next = l2->next;
                 l2 = NULL;
             }
             else if(!l1->next && !(l2&&l2->next) && former) {
                 // if l1 & l2 both end, we make a new node (assign to l1->next)
                 l1->next = new ListNode(0);
                 l2 = NULL;
             }
             if(l2) l2 = l2->next;
             l1 = l1->next;
         }
        return head;
    }
```
Note: This code is workable even when test case is like ***l1: 1->43 , l2: 21 ->9***

